{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30054,"record_hash":"sha256:d6d6cbe0da85864baa25346ffb06157c4636e9f10097668917b3c38e4cc93a63","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:26:08.236Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 855e7b\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1737\nOutput:\n}\n\nfn ceil_char_boundary(text: &str, index: usize) -> usize {\n    let mut index = index.min(text.len());\n    while !text.is_char_boundary(index) {\n        index += 1;\n    }\n    index\n}\n\n// GitMeta list order is storage order, not the public transcript ordering\n// contract. Readers should sort by transcript fields, primarily source_key and\n// record_index, when rendering a session timeline.\n#[derive(Serialize)]\nstruct TranscriptRecord<'a> {\n    source_key: &'a str,\n    record_index: usize,\n    record_hash: &'a str,\n    timestamp: Option<String>,\n    kind: RecordKind,\n    source_event_kind: String,\n    role: Option<String>,\n    text: Option<String>,\n    tool_name: Option<String>,\n    tool_input: Option<Value>,\n\nSlim normalized fields support timeline browsing and handoff without reparsing\nevery provider-specific record:\n\n- `kind`: provider-neutral timeline bucket: `message`, `tool_call`, or\n  `tool_result`\n- `source_event_kind`: provider event type, with a nested event type when obvious\n- `role` and `text`: conversation body when extraction is obvious\n- `tool_name` and `tool_input`: obvious tool activity\n- `source_record`: redacted provider record for provenance and future adapters\n\nSession metadata and unrecognized provider events are not persisted as\ntranscript records. Internal Codex `developer`/`system` role messages are also\nskipped. Codex `event_msg:user_message` and `event_msg:agent_message` wrappers\nare skipped because `response_item:message` carries the same text. For tool\nactivity, copied provider payload is intentionally slimmed. Message content\ncopied into `text`, tool call arguments/input copied into `tool_input`, and tool\nresult output copied into `text` are removed from `source_record`. Large\n`tool_result` text is capped at 4 KiB so one command cannot dominate the session\nrecord. Mixed provider content is kept when removing copied text would also drop\nuncopied sibling data.\n\nOmit repeated s\n[TRUNCATED]\nat means the transcript list must be readable without knowing the original\nmachine's file paths, working-directory state, branch state, or raw provider\nsession id.\n\nThe POC points at contextual handoff, not exact native session replay. Resuming\ninside the same provider as if the original transcript file still existed may\nneed a later native-transcript artifact or provider-specific reconstruction\nflow.\n\n## 2. Sharing Session Details\n\nA developer uses an agent to produce a change and opens a pull request. Reviewers\nshould eventually be able to open a GitButler web view showing what happened in\nthe agent session:\n\n- user prompts\n- assistant responses\n- tool calls\n- planning depth\n- discussed edge cases\n- follow-up questions\n\nThis helps reviewers understand whether the generated work was carefully guided\nor shallowly prompted. It also creates examples of good prompting patterns for a\nteam. A reviewer may later ask a follow-up question against that session context,\nfor example whether a payments edge case was considered.\n\nThe POC captures redacted session records and can write an explicit GitMeta\ntarget association. It does not create web links, publish metadata, infer\nownership, or attach sessions to pull requests automatically.\n\nExpected access pattern:\n\n1. start from a pull request, branch, change, or commit\n2. read its future `gitbutler:agent-sessions` relationship set\n3. resolve those session keys on the `project` target\n4. render each session's transcript timeline from the slim transcript records\n5. use redacted `source_record` for provenance and later normalization upgrades\n\nStored GitMeta list order is an implementation detail. A review UI should sort\nrecords by `source_key` and `record_index` for one source, and use `timestamp`,\n`source_key`, `record_index`, and `record_hash` when combining records from\nmultiple sources.\n\nThat means branch/PR metadata should point to sessions, not contain copies of\nsession transcripts.\n\n## Many-to-Many Relationships\n\nSessions and code review objects are not one-to-one.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:26:08.236Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}